        Infrastructure development in Nigeria | Global law firm | Norton Rose Fulbright        























































 Use of cookies byNorton Rose Fulbright
We use cookies to deliver our online services. Details and instructions on how to disable those cookies are set out at  nortonrosefulbright.com/cookies-policy. By continuing to use this website you agree to our use of our cookies unless you have disabled them.   




















        Infrastructure development in Nigeria | Global law firm | Norton Rose Fulbright        

















  




GlobalKnowledge
Publications








Infrastructure development in Nigeria



                            Publication | November 2013                        



The potential

The hurdles


Conclusion





The potential Nigeria has one of the most promising pipelines of infrastructure PPP projects in Africa. With a rapidly growing population and expected growth rates of at least 7 per cent over the next two years (as forecast by the IMF in May 2013), the need to develop the country’s infrastructure is paramount to allow the economy to continue to develop unchecked. Accordingly, Nigeria is the focus of a great deal of attention from the international infrastructure sector currently, as a result of its infrastructure gap and the commitment of federal and state governments to fill this gap.Unreliability of power infrastructure has no doubt been a factor in sluggish development in certain parts of the economy, particular in process plant related industries. However, as a number of newly-financed IPPs come on line in the next few years, assisted by Nigeria’s power privatisation initiative, the increasing stability of power infrastructure and increased exposure of international and local investors, as well as development finance institutions (DFIs) and export credit agencies (ECAs), to the Nigerian market should assist the process of developing Nigeria’s anticipated pipeline of infrastructure projects.Lagos State, as the economic powerhouse of the country, is leading the way in this regard. With a population of over 17 million, and growing by a further half million every year, Lagos has published a clear 10-point plan to improve key aspects of its public infrastructure and avoid the city grinding to a halt.Its longer-term plan includes a number of improvements which are expected to:minimise transport bottlenecks (such as the recently completed Ikoyi-Lekki bridge and the anticipated Fourth Mainland Bridge)improve transport links to population centres and new industrial zones (such as the Lekki-Epe Expressway),improve general economic development (such as the creation of a master plan for the development of the Lekki peninsula east of Lagos, including to date the establishment of two free trade zones).create additional transport modes (such as the Lagos Metro Blue Line (in construction) and Red Line (route secured), as well as the new Lekki-Epe International Airport (currently in procurement))The importance of the Lekki peninsula as an axis for growth is underlined by the proposed greenfield deep sea Lekki Port, where financing is currently being put in place. This estimated $1.5 billion project about 60km east of the existing Lagos ports (Apapa, Tincan Island and Kirikiri) is being constructed within a free trade zone and is expected to provide an additional 2.5 million twenty-foot equivalent unit (TEU) capacity into the Nigerian container terminal market, offering a quicker and less-congested route to market for goods, and accommodating larger-capacity ships and using state-of-the-art facilities. The project is being led by the Singapore-based Tolaram group to complement its existing operations in Nigeria, with major co-investments being made at both state level (by Lagos State) and federal level (through the Nigerian Ports Authority), and also supported by International Container Terminal Services Inc of Philippines as the proposed operator.The development of public infrastructure is occurring in tandem with a huge expansion in private sector developments. In particular there are accelerating signs of growth in the property development market in Nigeria. Continuing urbanisation, an emerging middle class and a shortfall in high quality office space for international and domestic companies are key drivers for the wave of real estate developments such as retail malls, business parks and office space.Developments such as the Ikeja City Mall and Palms Shopping Mall in Lagos State, and Polo Park in Enugu State are at the forefront of the expanding retail market, with other developments such as the Osapa Convenience Centre on the Lekki-Epe Express Way in Lagos following in the tailwind. There is no shortage of companies looking to take long leaseholds of units, with the likes of Shoprite, Game and Pick n Pay leading the expansion across Africa. Office space is also developing at a pace, with the Wings Office Towers on Victoria Island and Heritage Place in the Ikoyi district of Lagos being two standout Grade A offices under development.The success of ambitious infrastructure projects such as Lekki Port would likely increase investors’ appetite to expand their operations and capture the anticipated growth. The Economist reported in September 2013 that Shoprite’s goods were taking 117 days to reach market in Nigeria, with port congestion in Lagos being a major contributor to this delay. The expansion of port capacity will therefore assist those seeking to expand their business routes into and out of Nigeria, and have substantial positive macroeconomic effect. 

The hurdles


Investment in these projects is, of course, not without its risks. Whilst some market-risk private sector projects have already successfully closed in Nigeria in recent years without any government support (such as the Nigerian-led Main One telecommunications cable between Nigeria, Ghana and Portugal, and telecoms towers developments led principally by IHS and Helios), for those projects with a key public sector delivery component, a number of key aspects will need to be in place to ensure swift closure of projects and to allow the pipeline of projects to reach its potential.Governmental support. Supporting infrastructure to the project site, whether by way of new roads or capacity upgrades to existing roads and junctions, can be a key area where government policy or undertakings can provide comfort to a greenfield project. It may be difficult to obtain fixed commitments for this, as government departments will be reluctant to commit to major expenditure on their own part until there is some certainty as to the required traffic. Without infrastructure support, however, it may be more difficult to finance the project. On some projects, the success of the project may be dependent on the delivery of essential government services, and it would be wise to structure this type of support with key service-level deliverables that the concessionaire and lenders can rely on.Credit support. The size and nature of the project may mean that additional government comfort is required to support the obligations of the relevant state agencies entering into any long-term concession contracts. Federal government support will not by itself allow a project to reach investment-grade status. DFIs will therefore continue to play an important part during this phase of infrastructure development, and in addition to mainstays such as African Development Bank and IFC, other institutions such as European Investment Bank and Islamic Development Bank are also gearing up to provide significant finance to Nigerian projects. Additional credit support arrangements such as political risk insurance (PRI) cover and ECA coverage will also play a necessary part of the funding mix for the project, although this too will add to the complexity of the projects.Exit strategy. A critical issue for lenders and other investors will be the level of government underpinning for their investment in a termination scenario, particularly on a concessionaire default. In Nigeria’s current state of PPP development, the level of necessary support is likely to remain extremely high. Not all project eventualities can be foreseen, and circumstances may arise where the project needs to be terminated or otherwise handed back to the government. This is a very topical issue, given Lagos State’s recent announcement that it had bought out 100 per cent of the equity in Lekki Concession Company Ltd (the concessionaire on the Lekki-Epe Expressway PPP since 2008) effectively returning the project back into state government control. One of the other major concession projects in the region, the Murtala Mohammed II domestic airport terminal concession, being operated by Bi-Courtney Limited, has also been the subject of very public court battles against the federal government to enforce the concessionaire’s exclusivity rights at the airport. Although Bi-Courtney most recently succeeded in court in restraining the federal government, this episode suggests that investors may need to be prepared to go to some lengths to protect their economic interests, which should either be dealt with through appropriate dispute resolution structures or otherwise factored into the risk profile for the project.Robust contract structures. Even with the above arrangements in place, the robustness of the project contract structures (such as EPC and O&M contracts) can have a large role to play in ensuring the bankability of the project. There are recent examples on Nigerian projects of subcontractors taking an enhanced role in providing protection for the concessionaire in certain project distress situations, for the benefit of the lenders. The lenders may also expect project throughputs to be guaranteed to particular levels or for these to be demonstrated by the concessionaire obtaining a sufficient level of long-term usage contracts.




Conclusion


Nigeria is now so strategically important that it cannot be ignored by investors, and increasing international interest is being matched by increased commitment by DFIs. Nigerian infrastructure PPPs to date have had a rocky start, but the market outlook still remains promising to those prepared to work hard and find an appropriate balance of risks and opportunity that will allow their project to stand the test of time.



 



 

					Sector:
					
Infrastructure, mining and commodities 
 






 
